description.en: The ontolgy represents AI risk concepts and relations based on the AI Act draft and ISO 31000 standard series.

comment.en: Refers to management and operation of critical infrastructure

activities carried out by law enforcement authorities for the prevention, investigation, detection or prosecution of criminal offences or the execution of criminal penalties, including the safeguarding against and the prevention of threats to public security [Source: AI Act, Article 3(41)]
Indicates an element that has the potential give rise to a risk.
the ability of an AI system to achieve its intended purpose [Source: AI Act, Article 3(18)]
Refers to incompentece of individuals to whom human oversight is assigned.

label.en: Lack Of Appropriate Instruction For Use

comment.en: Refers to the purpose of determining access or assigning natural persons to educational and vocational training institutions.
Measure that maintains and/or modifies risk. [Source: ISO 31000, 3.8]
Refers to a group of persons such as citizens, marginsalised groups, etc.

data used for providing an evaluation of the trained AI system and for tuning its non-learnable parameters and its learning process, among other things, in order to prevent overfitting; whereas the validation dataset can be a separate dataset or part of the training dataset, either as a fixed or variable split [Source: AI Act, Article 3(30)]
Refers to EU Charter of Fundamental Rights, Art. 8 (protection of personal data)

predicting the occurrence or reoccurrence of an actual or potential criminal offence based on profiling of natural persons or assessing personality traits and characteristics or past criminal behaviour of natural persons or groups
Refers to profiling of natural persons in the course of detection, investigation or prosecution of criminal offences.
Refers to manipulating or generating audio content.

label.en: Disruption Of Operation Of Critical Infrastructure

comment.en: inputs designed to cause the model to make a mistake

Represents a software that is developed with one or more of the AI Approaches and can, for a given set of human-defined objectives, generate outputs such as content, predictions, recommendations, or decisions influencing the environments they interact with. [Source: AI Act, Art 3(1)]
Refers to the main approaches and techniques used for development of AI systems.
Chance of an event happening. [Source: ISO 31000, 3.7]

Refers to use of AI systems for making individual risk assessments of natural persons in order to assess the risk of a natural person for offending or reoffending or the risk for potential victims of criminal offences.
Specifies the extent to which the outcome produced with an AI system is easily reversible.
Indicates a right, freedom, or principle set out in the EU Charter of Fundamental Rights.
Refers to EU Charter of Fundamental Rights, Art. 21

Refers to the use for which an AI system is intended by the provider, including the specific context and conditions of use, as specified in the information supplied by the provider in the instructions for use, promotional or sales materials and statements, as well as in the technical documentation. [Source: AI Act, Art 3(12)]

deploying subliminal techniques beyond a person’s consciousness in order to materially distort a person’s behaviour in a manner that causes or is likely to cause that person or another person physical or psychological harm
Refers to manipulating or generating image content.
Outcome of an event affecting objectives. [Source: ISO 31000, 3.6]
the extent to which an AI system has been used or is likely to be used
data provided to or directly acquired by an AI system on the basis of which the system produces an output [Source: AI Act, Article 3(32)]
data used for training an AI system through fitting its learnable parameters, including the weights of a neural network [Source: AI Act, Article 3(29)]

data used for providing an independent evaluation of the trained and validated AI system in order to confirm the expected performance of that system before its placing on the market or putting into service [Source: AI Act, Article 3(31)]

use of an AI system in a way that is not in accordance with its intended purpose, but which may result from reasonably foreseeable human behaviour or interaction with other systems [Source: AI Act, Article 3(13)]
Any individual, group or organization that can affect, be affected by or perceive itself to be affected by a decision or activity[Source: ISO/IEC TR 24028, 3.37]
Represents occurrence or change of a particular set of circumstances. [Source ISO 31000, 3.5]
tendency of automatically relying or over-relying on the output produced by an AI system.
The use of an AI system in a way that is not in accordance with its intended purpose.

comment.en: the purpose of identifying natural persons at a distance through the comparison of a person’s biometric data with the biometric data contained in a reference database
Attack trying to manipulate the training dataset
Refers to the purpose of assessing students in educational and vocational training institutions and for assessing participants in tests commonly required for admission to educational institutions.
Employment, workers management and access to self-employment
Weakness of a system can be exploited by one or more threats. [Source: ISO/IEC TR 24028, 3.48 with modifications]
inacurracy of the predictions, recommondations, or decisions produced by the system.

any incident that directly or indirectly leads, might have led or might lead to : (a) the death of a person or serious damage to a person’s health, to property or the environment, (b) a serious and irreversible disruption of the management and operation of critical infrastructure [Source: AI Act, Articl3 3(44)]
Indicates a risk (of harm) associated with an AI system.
Refers to manipulating or generating video content.
Indicates vulnerabilities of an AI system.

label.en: Indicates the intended purpose of an AI system.

comment.en: Indicates stakeholders of an AI system
Indicates the AI techniques used in an AI system.
